1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation, a great place to start when learning the French. It teaches the reader how to cope with playing with a locked pawn structure as well as the minor piece dynamic of the c8/Bad/French Bishop. }
3... c5 { We are able to outline the standard break against the space. } 4. c3
{ 4.dxc5  It is an important note to keep in mind when playing the French when White makes this capture it significantly weakens the e-pawn for the long-term, creating a target. }
4... Ne7 { Our starting move to begin our plan of trading off the Bad Bishop. }
5. Nf3 Nec6 6. Bd3
{ By far the main move here.   6.Be2  will be handled in the same manner in this variation.   White's only real alternative is  6.a3  which we will investigate in the next overview variation. }
6... b6 7. O-O Ba6
{ It would be inaccurate to play another move before ...Ba6.   For instance, if  7...Be7  White can play  8.Re1  and meet  8...Ba6  with  9.Bc2  - avoiding the trade of Bishops.  The immediate ...Ba6 exploits the fact that White's bishop is pinned to his rook. }
8. Bxa6
{ The most common move in practice. Overall, this is a rare guest in tournament play which makes 4... Ne7 a great surprise weapon.   8.Re1  Bxd3  Now that White can play  Bc2  we trade off the bishops.  9.Qxd3  Be7  Black achieves normal development and queenside expansion. Without a light-squared bishop, White finds it very difficult to attack on the kingside. }
8... Nxa6 9. Qa4 Nb8 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. Qg4 h5
{ A novelty investigated in the main text. } *

