1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The most aggressive of all of the options against the French  (and statistically the most frequently seen)  . }
3... Nf6 4. e5
{ The Classical Variation. Without the trade of the Bishops, this feature adds more counterplay for both players. }
4... Nfd7 5. f4 c5
{ The thematic break in the position, White takes space and we attempt to knock it down. }
6. Nf3 Be7 { Our move to invoke White's full aggression, flexible and good. }
7. Be3 O-O
{ This move order is deliberate, we are keeping our queenside developmental options open. }
8. Qd2 { The most popular move in practice. } 8... b6
{ In many lines we have left the option open to play Ba6. } 9. Nd1
{ This was a main line in the past as it was covered by GM Negi in his Grandmaster Repertoire series. Things changed, however, when Harikrishna won a nice game against Giri using a fresh idea.   9.O-O-O  A move that can be expected to be seen in practice frequently. White feels safe, we have only aggression for him.  9...Nc6  10.Kb1  c4  11.f5  b5  Gets nasty as seen in the major variations. It is strongly suggested that in this type of tactical slugfest that the reader plays around with the engine in these positions to play devils advocate to learn tactical patterns associated with the variation. }
9... a5
{ A very nice idea of expanding on the queenside and preparing typical play. }
10. c3 a4 { A touch of space... } 11. Bd3 Ba6
{ It feels better to wait for White to develop the light-squared bishop before we offer the trade. Trying to coax the stutter step and loss of tempo by White. }
12. O-O Nc6
{ As in: Giri, A. - Harikrishna, P., 0-1, 4th Norway Chess 2016. Black will trade on d3 and push on the queenside. We don't need to fear White's f5 advance. It is usually not even advisable to take on f5 - just weather the storm while you break through on the queenside. With the light-squared bishops off, White's attack loses a lot of its bite. }
