1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ The most aggressive move in the position. } 4... Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bxe7
{ It should always alarm us when our strong Bishop is traded off while our 'French Bishop' remains. }
6... Qxe7 7. f4
{ A key moment in understanding for Black. Should we play the direct c5 or should we play a6 to stop b5? }
7... a6
{ It is very important to play a6 here before b5 to stop the Nb5 idea. The rule with when to play a6 is simple: When the move Nb5 comes with the dual threat of Nd6+ and Nc7+ we need to play a6 before c5. If our King was castled it would only be the threat of Nc7 which is easy to fix. }
8. Nf3 c5 9. dxc5 Nc6
{ We are waiting to capture on c5, the pawn goes nowhere. } 10. Qd2
{ 10.Bd3  The other move investigated in the course, transpositions occur with this move in conjunction with  Qd2. }
10... Nxc5 11. O-O-O b5
{ We will not waste any time here getting the ball rolling on the attack. } 12.
Bd3 b4
{ We begin action against the White King and vacate the light squares for our Bishop to become useful. }
13. Ne2 a5
{ A key move and Memory Marker as it is the key starting point for the plan of activating the 'French Bishop'. }
14. Ned4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 O-O 16. Kb1 Ba6
{ This move gets rid of our 'French Bishop' and follows the example game: Khachiyan, Melikset - Akobian, Varuzhan, 0-1, World op 36th, 2008. }
