1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation. This is the first variation that an aspiring French player should learn since it exemplifies many of the common positional and structural ideas in the French. Before we begin to learn moves, we should take a moment to understand the nature of the position and our goals for play. With 3 e5, White has defined the position in two ways: The pawn structure has become closed and Black is playing with less space. In a more concrete interpretation, White has voluntarily overextended his center with the trade-off that Black will have more difficult piece development and a weaker kingside. Accordingly we can understand that Black's play and development should revolve around attacking White's overextended center and finding a harmonious scheme of development with potential for exchanging off Black's poorly placed pieces.  This fixing of the pawn structure now clearly defines the Bishops. When evaluating the French Bishop  (c8 Bishop)  we need to define and understand the concept of ‘good versus bad’ A Good Bishop is on the opposite color as its pawns. A Bad Bishop is on the same color as its pawns. This is directly applicable to the central pawn structure as any endgame with Good Bishop versus Bad Bishop with equal pawns will result in a position of ‘playing for two results’ for the Good Bishop wielder.  Across nearly all variations in the French we will need to handle the issue of our French Bishop. }
3... c5 4. c3 Ne7
{ This scheme of development is a specialty of GM Georg Meier. The g8-knight relocates to c6 to prepare ...b6 and ...Ba6.   A more mainstream option of  4...Qb6  will be offered in informational variations at the end of the chapter.   To overemphasize, this key move and major Memory Marker for the variation initiates the overall plan of trading off our Bad Bishop on c8, 'The French Bishop'. }
5. Nf3 Nec6
{ One of the reasons we start with ...Ne7 and ...Nec6 is because it blocks the diagonal to our king. If we started with ...b6 and ...Ba6, White could trade bishops and then have Qa4+ to win a piece. }
