3... Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7
{ Other Knight moves simply will not do  5...Ne4  has been tried for shock value but White has his choice of different paths to a better position. For instance GM Berg played  6.Bxe7  Qxe7  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.a3  c5  Qg4  and went on to win easily. }
6. h4
{ White gambits a pawn reaching the Alekhine-Chatard Attack. This sacrifice is very dangerous for Black practically because White's attacking play is natural and the correct defense is often very computer-like. It is therefore our recommendation to just decline the gambit and get a decent position. Black should keep in mind in all variations that White will have an advantage on the kingside play because of the cramping e5 pawn. Black's domain will always be the queenside. Consequently, Black will only rarely castle kingside. }
