{ We will start by looking at White's options that aren't Bxe7. This line is becoming more popular recently as well. The response 7...c5 has pretty much been been Black's only response in the position, but here we have an interesting novelty that again takes the sting out of White's attack. }
7... h5
{ We know that White wants to play Qg4, so why not play ...h5 and lock White's kingside play before we counter-attack on the queenside? The nice thing about this move is that it allows us to combine both the 7 Be3 and 7 Bf4 sidelines into a position with identical plans. The engines also validate this move as perfectly playable. Objectively 7...c5 should be recognized as the most critical move, but 7...h5 is a sound alternative and we prefer to stay out of White's comfort zone. }
8. Qf3
{ The best try according to the engine. This has a similar flavor to the mainlines with Qg4, but here Black is always able to respond with ...g6 since we don't have to worry about White playing h5 to break our structure. }
